#* '''1777''', {{w|Samuel Johnson}}, “Life of the Author” in ''The Works of {{w|Richard Savage (poet)|Richard Savage}} with an Account of the Life and Writings of the Author'', London: T. Evans, Volume I, p. lxi,<sup>[https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000780477]</sup>
#*: The reigning error of his life was, that he '''mistook''' the love for the practice of virtue, and was indeed not so much a good man, as the friend of goodness.
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[misunderstand]] (someone).
#* {{circa|1595}} {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Richard II (play)|Richard II}}'', Act II, Scene 3,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=richard2&Act=2&Scene=3&Scope=scene]</sup>
#*: '''Mistake''' me not, my lord; ’tis not my meaning
#*: To raze one title of your honour out:
#* '''1749''', {{w|Henry Fielding}}, ''{{w|The History of Tom Jones, a Foundling}}'', Dublin: John Smith, Volume 1, Book 3, Chapter 6, pp. 122-123,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004794856.0001.001]</sup>
#*: {{...}} at last she so evidently demonstrated her Affection to him to be much stronger than what she bore her own Son, that it was impossible to '''mistake''' her any longer.
# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To commit an unintentional [[error]]; to do or think something wrong.
#* {{circa|1598}} {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Much Ado about Nothing}}'', Act V, Scene 1,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=muchado&Act=5&Scene=1&Scope=scene]</sup>
#*: Impose me to what penance your invention
#*: Can lay upon my sin: yet sinn’d I not
#*: But in '''mistaking'''.
#* '''1720''', {{w|Jonathan Swift}}, “Letter to a Young Clergyman” in ''The Works of Jonathan Swift'', London: Charles Elliot, 1784, Volume 10, pp. 6-7,<sup>[https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/008661469]</sup>
